    "body": "### Describe the bug\r\n\r\nFunctions such as `getline` and `getbufline` convert null characters in a file into newline characters in the list of strings they return. This is probably because of `:h NL-used-for-NUL`.\r\n\r\nAs neovim inserts null characters instead of newlines for multiline completion (https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/7769), today with LSP null characters keep appear in code. Any plugin which does not handle this case specially will get confused on what the actual content of the file is. I encountered this when using [vim-lsp](https://github.com/prabirshrestha/vim-lsp). This LSP client joins the lines returned by `getbufline` by `\\n`, and then sends the result to an LSP server. Therefore, after a null appears in the file, both the client and the server think there's an extra `\\n`, where there actually is a null, and cannot sync properly with the actual content of the file.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n```\r\nA\r\nB\r\nC\r\n```\r\nIf you open a file with such contents, insert a null character after the `B` (this can be done by `CTRL-V CTRL-J` in normal mode, and neovim renders the null character as `^@`), what appears on the screen becomes\r\n```\r\nA\r\nB^@\r\nC\r\n```\r\nThen `:echo getline(1, '$')`, you'll get\r\n```\r\n['A', 'B\r\n', 'C']\r\n```\r\ninstead of `['A', 'B^@', 'C']`.\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\n`getline` and `getbufline` return the actual content of the file, including of the null characters.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\n0.8.2\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nyes, vim 9.0\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nLinux 6.1.8-arch1-1\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nalacritty 0.11.0\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nalacritty\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nArch Linux official repository (pacman)",
